To make sure that signal is send correctly we need to update variable used in dbus. Also let's avoid making copy of newVal.

(const auto& newVal, auto& oldVal) {
   *oldVal = newVal; // thanks to that sdbusplus known that value has changed and signal needs to be send
}

Yes, there are few cases where you cannot or don't want to use auto.

You cannot use auto in some usecases with templates, for example in async_method_call you cannot use auto as lambda parameters because these parameters are used to deduce type of dbus interface.

You may don't want to use auto in case of conversions for example:
    const auto text = std::vector<std::string>({"line1", "line2"});
    for (std::string_view item : text) {
        std::cout << item << std::endl;
    }

I think we could do this before emplace. This way memory will be lazy initialized and reports that are never triggered will consume no memory.

vec.reserve(maxSize);
vec.emplace_back(...);
